Love reviews from my workshop attendees.
This was my smallest workshop so far. But the most beautiful experience. Thank you for the gift too
Here are Sadia's words (first time attendee of my workshop)

"This HENNA Meetup has been one of my best in person workshops I have ever attended and I’m already feeling delighted to have been able to be a part of this and learning to follow your (best approach ) skills and techniques to have our foot prints with more positively in our henna society. 

Any students learn well when the teacher is transparent, honest and passionate about teaching. You are the perfect example for it. I had some sort of knowledge about henna but there’s no limit on learning new things and I accomplished a lot of things Bhavna.  Specially mapping, trying small segments and build upon it, also using the right materials with setups etc.

I want to pause and mention that, all of you are absolutely amazing and I learned a lot different things from you all (Sophie, Ashlesha, Krupali).

Last but not least if any of you specifically Bhavna ever need anything that is in my range I will never hesitate. I am super grateful to know you at least a bit and it was such an amazing experience to have a little bonding with you all!!! I thank Lord for this experience in my short journey in this world. And I can’t wait to be a part of it again.Take care you all and enjoy the holidays a head of you and Safe trip Bhavna!"

Thank you Sadia @hennafy for your kind words and love and affection.

#hennaworkshop#hennajourney#learnhenna

Thank you Krupali ( second time attendee) @hennabykrupali for such a warm review.
Thank you for the gift too.

"Thank YOU Bhavna for everything you did to ensure we achieve our goals! You don’t just teach, you inspire! And you’ve been an inspiration from me from the first day I met you 🥹 Thank you for welcoming us into your home, and being so so so kind. From letting us stay over, to making delicious food for us - you’ve been an absolute gem! Thank you for everything! I wish you and your family all the health, happiness and success in life 😊

I had a wonderful time, and I’m so glad I was able to make it to this weekend to meet all of you amazing souls 💕"

#learnhenna#hennaworkshop #hennajourney

Hello dear friends, anybody who knows me knows that if I am asking for something, it is truly truly for someone else who needs help and is in a situation that may God forbid never happens to anyone.
I have a friend. Her sister was diagnosed with breast cancer, needs a lot of treatment and is currently out of a job which also translates to no insurance. She needs to pay for her own insurance and that itself without an income is a crazy thing to do each month. Expecting to pay about $700 for insurance out of pocket without a job and being a single mom is something really very difficult.
Today I asked every person I know for a little help whether it be $20, $40 or if your gracious enough and you have a little spare money this season instead of buying some gifts. Please donate the gift of life to this lovely woman. Send a little more if you can or send something regularly if you can.
This person needs treatment for many, many months ahead. A lot of surgeries coming up. As you can understand, breast cancer isn't an easy journey.
Please DM me for zelle details.
Or please let me know if you want to donate and cash.

Hoping and praying that everyone has a safe, healthy end of 2022 and a very hopeful and happy, healthy 2023.

If you wish to come over to my place to get some henna which I will offer you in place of donations. Please DM me so we can set up a date ASAP.

If you are an artist, you will criticize yourself. If you do not succeed in the timeline that you created for yourself, you will criticize yourself. You would doubt your abilities, but do not listen to that voice, change that voice tell yourselves it takes time it’s OK if it takes time, tell yourself to Be Patient ,Be Positive, Be Persistent and keep at it do not give up your dreams Being a full-time artist doesn’t happen overnight it takes time and patience and a whole lot of I believe this will happen attitude. To anybody out there who is trying their best. My best wishes are with you if you ever need any guidance in the Henna world I am right here for you. “We got this”

My setup for bridal henna..get set go...
Two padded chairs to folding TV dinner tables to clip-on lights with USB which can go into an extension cord that also has USB plug points, a heater, stools, a director's chair for doing feet and a padded ergonomic pillow for the bride to sit on in the director's chair.

 If you are a bridal henna artist and you want any answers to your burning questions, feel free to DM me. I'm here to help.

The setup has helped me immensely with so many years of doing henna inspired of my back issues which I have from childhood.

Pros of hiring a professional henna artist

Homemade natural henna

Years of knowledge and experience

Neat and fast designs

Brings own setup

Makes a contract

Gives realistic estimate of time needed to complete the task

Gives right aftercare for good stain

Brings aftercare kit for bride

Provides pre care instructions to bride

Fabulous artwork will make you happy and get you lots of compliments during your wedding festivities.

Cons of hiring an Unprofessional 

They buy store bought henna which contains chemicals and preservatives

If they say they make henna it could be with PPD hair dye and not therapeutic grade essential oils

PPD henna causes rashes, burns, scars and organ failure. (google ppd poisoning)

They don 't bring a setup

They do not make a contract

They do not show up in some cases (no contract means no commitment)

They take much longer to do the henna and the designs can look like scribbles

They do not know proper aftercare for henna

Need I say more..

Remember
Henna is your first vendor for your wedding and henna stays with you long after your wedding.
Henna constitutes less than 1 % of your whole wedding budget
so
PLEASE
give your professional henna artist the respect and the $$ she deserves

(bills get paid with $$)

Industry standard rates in the US are between $95-$150 per hour for professional artists.

It's that time of year again. This year's Henna Journey Workshop 
will be 
December 16th and 17th with a meet and greet on 15th evening in Clarksburg, Maryland. Meals will be provided.
If interested, DM or email me at bhavnashenna@gmail.com

This workshop will help you understand layouts and how to build designs from scratch with elements like peacocks, elephants,flowers and figures along with intricate fills and grids to enhance the design.
Most importantly, it will also teach you how to set up and work with the client, including how to prep beforehand with homemade henna and aftercare.

Let's not forget the back end work of a henna artist. How to create contracts and be a good ethical business person.

If you're interested in this workshop, it will not only give you the skills you need to build on your previous skills, but will also bring you. Lots of love, laughter, joy and friendship.

$250 for two full days of instruction, hands-on practice and meals provided.

Five lucky students will get to stay with me and save on hotel costs 

If you question, who is a good candidate for this workshop? My answer would be anyone who wants to improve their skills and get better at henna cuz we all need to improve even when we think we have reached a certain level of being an artist.

#learnhenna#hennaworkshop#hennajourney

The tradition of applying henna on the hands and feet of the bride before the wedding is a common practice in many cultures. This is known as bridal henna, and it is an important part of the wedding preparations.

Bridal henna is not just a form of body art but also a symbol of love and affection. The intricate designs are created using natural henna paste that is made from the leaves of the henna plant. The paste is applied to the skin using a cone or brush, and left to dry for several hours.

The bride usually sits still during the application process, surrounded by her close family and friends. It is a time for bonding and celebration as they prepare for the wedding.

Once the henna paste has dried, it is removed to reveal a rich reddish-brown stain. The color gradually darkens over the next few days, and can last up to two weeks.

Bridal henna is not just a beautiful decoration, but also a way to honor tradition and express creativity. It serves as a reminder of the joyous occasion and the love shared between the newlyweds.

Bridal Henna, also known as Mehndi, is an important pre-wedding ritual in Indian culture. It is a form of temporary skin decoration that is applied to the bride's hands and feet by a skilled henna artist. The intricate designs are made using a paste made of dried henna leaves, lemon juice, and essential oils. The paste is applied using a cone-shaped tube, and the designs can take anywhere from a few hours to a few days to dry and set.

Bridal Henna is not just a form of decoration, but it also has cultural and religious significance. It is believed to bring good luck and prosperity to the bride and her new family. The designs often include symbols and motifs that represent fertility, love, and blessings.

Apart from the bride, other women in the family and close friends also get henna applied to their hands and feet as a part of the celebration. It is a time to bond, share stories, and enjoy each other's company.

Overall, Bridal Henna is an integral part of Indian culture and continues to be a cherished tradition that is passed on from generation to generation.
